ttle about how racial and ethnic groups organize and participate in politics or how political elites try to mobilize them. This book tells us. By integrating class-based factors with racial and ethnic factors, Jan Leighley shows what motivates African-Americans, Latinos, and Anglos to mobilize and participate in politics. Drawing on national survey data and on interviews with party and elected officials in Texas, she develops a nuanced understanding of how class, race, and ethnicity act as individual and contextual influences on elite mobilization and mass participation. Leighley examines whether the diverse theoretical approaches generally used to explain individual participation in politics are supported for the groups under consideration. She concludes that the political and social context influences racial and ethnic minorities' decisions to participate, but that different features of those environments are important for different groups. Race and ethnicity structure participation more than previous research suggests. Casting new light on an issue at the crux of contemporary American politics, Strength in Numbers? will be welcomed by scholars and students of political science, African-American and Latino studies, urban politics, and social movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aMinoritiesxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aPolitical participationzUnited States. 0aPolitiskt deltagande. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aAbraham, Henry J.  aAbramson, Paul R.  aAffigne, Anthony.  aArvizu, John R.  aBobo, Lawrence.  aBrishetto, Robert.  aCalvo, Maria Antonia.  aCampbell, Angus.  aCarson, Claybome.  aCitizen Participation Survey.  aDavidson, Chandler.  aDukakis, Michael.  aFarley, Reynolds.  aFlores, Henry.  aFrymer, Paul.  aHansen, John Mark.